To achieve the desired outcome of splitting Quarkus-specific tests from other types, the following Gradle changes will be required:

1. Define a new sourceSet.
```
sourceSets {
    smokeTest {
        compileClasspath += main.output
        runtimeClasspath += main.output
        java {
            srcDir file(&#39;src/smokeTest/java&#39;)
        }
        resources.srcDir file(&#39;src/smokeTest/resources&#39;)
    }
}
```
2. Create custom configuration that extends from test.
```
configurations {
    smokeTestImplementation.extendsFrom(testImplementation)
    smokeTestRuntimeOnly.extendsFrom(testRuntimeOnly)
}
```

3. Define a custom task of type Test.
```
task smokeTest(type: Test) {
    description = &quot;Run smoke tests&quot;
    group = &quot;verification&quot;
    testClassesDirs = sourceSets.smokeTest.output.classesDirs
    classpath = sourceSets.smokeTest.runtimeClasspath
}
```
4. Any dependencies required for the new sourceSet / Task should be included in `test` scope.
```
dependencies {
    testImplementation &quot;org.junit.jupiter:${jupiterVersion}&quot; 
// This is used for unit tests under &#39;test&#39; directory.

    testImplementation &quot;io.rest-assured:rest-assured:${restAssuredVersion}&quot; 
// This is in same scope as unit tests but are smoke test dependencies
}
```

Write your new tests.
```
├── main
├── test
│   ├── java
│   └── resources
├── smokeTest
│   ├── java
│   └── resources
```
Any resources required by the new directory will also be in the `test`/resources directory.  This is likely a small issue with my configuration and could be corrected to pull from the appropriate directory, but it also helps when tests need to share the same resources, e.g. import.sql.

Addressing the original Class Cast Exception issue; I am guessing but think that the method Quarkus uses for swapping out core components for test vs dev vs prod is the source.  As I roughly understand it, Quarkus would use a different ClassLoader, for example, so when the Quarkus Test Extension tries to load BuildChainBuilder its using a production version and not the non-prod type.

