As I understood your question: you would like to populate sets of data, and then flush that data occasionally from different user requests.  

This leads to extended persistence context... Which was a thing in 2007 and in fully serverside applications, like JSF. And this is not what people usually do in spring or in any other stateless microservices world now.

What I can see - you are trying to mix service layer (application SPI) and persistence layer (application implementation). 

What I would suggest for you to reorganize your code: introduce a stateful service.


    @ApplicationScoped
    public class DataService {
    
       private final DataRepository repository; 
    
       private List&lt;Data&gt; currentDataSet;
    
       private ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();
    
       @Inject
       public DataService(DataRepository dataRepository) {
          this.repository = repository;
          this.currentDataSet = new LinkedList&lt;&gt;();
       }
    
       public void add(Data data) {
           lock.lock();
           try {
              this.currentDataSet.add(data);
           } finally {
              lock.unlock();
           }
       }
    
       @Transactional
       public void flush() {
          lock.lock();
    
          final List&lt;Data&gt; dataToPersist;
    
          try {
             dataToPersist = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(this.currentDataSet);
             dataToPersist.forEach(repository::save);
             dataToPersist.flush();
             this.currentDataSet = new LinkedList&lt;&gt;();
          } finally {
             lock.unlock()
          }
        }
    }

And your DataRepository should implement 2 methods: 

    save(Data data) {
       setReferences(data);
       entityManager.perist(data);
    }
    
    flush() {
       entityManager.flush();
    }


With this - you are operating with a `DataService`, and persistence layer is somewhere hidden from client of `DataService`. 

But this kind of writing would make your application not horizontally scalable.  Then it would be best if you considered writing your data in the `DataService` to some shared in-memory storage, like Hazelcast or Redis instead of the in-current-jvm-memory `currentDataSet` list. And with this, you would achieve scalability.

And one more hint -&gt; even though it is a good promise to have the same data in persistence and in SPI and in API - in practice, it works well for primitive use cases, for something more serious you should have separate data models for API, service and persistence layers and corresponding mappings. Yes, this is EE Java - and it pays out in long run. As a first start, I would suggest having only 2: API (shared with service) and Persistence layer data models.

