I don&#39;t have the book, but that quote mentions bound &quot;content&quot;, and so the only reasonable thing it could be talking about is the [`#bindContent(ObservableList)`][1]&lt;sup&gt;**1**&lt;/sup&gt; method. If you call that method, then changes to the `ObservableList` will be reflected in the `ListProperty`&lt;sup&gt;**2**&lt;/sup&gt; but not vice versa.

For example:

```lang-java
import javafx.beans.property.ListProperty;
import javafx.beans.property.SimpleListProperty;
import javafx.collections.FXCollections;
import javafx.collections.ObservableList;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ObservableList&lt;String&gt; foo = FXCollections.observableArrayList();
        ObservableList&lt;String&gt; bar = FXCollections.observableArrayList();

        ListProperty&lt;String&gt; property = new SimpleListProperty&lt;&gt;(foo);
        property.bindContent(bar);

        bar.add(&quot;Hello&quot;);
        // same as &#39;property.get().add(&quot;World&quot;)&#39; (i.e., adds directly to &#39;foo&#39;)
        property.add(&quot;World&quot;);

        System.out.println(&quot;FOO: &quot; + foo);
        System.out.println(&quot;BAR: &quot; + bar);
    }
}
```

Output:

```lang-none
FOO: [Hello, World]
BAR: [Hello]
```

You can use the [`#bindContentBidirectional(ObservableList)`][2]&lt;sup&gt;**1**&lt;/sup&gt; method instead if you want changes to be reflected in both directions. 

For example:

```lang-java
import javafx.beans.property.ListProperty;
import javafx.beans.property.SimpleListProperty;
import javafx.collections.FXCollections;
import javafx.collections.ObservableList;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ObservableList&lt;String&gt; foo = FXCollections.observableArrayList();
        ObservableList&lt;String&gt; bar = FXCollections.observableArrayList();

        ListProperty&lt;String&gt; property = new SimpleListProperty&lt;&gt;(foo);
        // only change from previous example
        property.bindContentBidirectional(bar);

        bar.add(&quot;Hello&quot;);
        // same as &#39;property.get().add(&quot;World&quot;)&#39; (i.e., adds directly to &#39;foo&#39;)
        property.add(&quot;World&quot;);

        System.out.println(&quot;FOO: &quot; + foo);
        System.out.println(&quot;BAR: &quot; + bar);
    }
}
```

Output:

```lang-none
FOO: [Hello, World]
BAR: [Hello, World]
```

---

&lt;sup&gt;**1.** These methods are declared in the [`ReadOnlyListProperty`][3] class. Note the &quot;read-only&quot; bit only refers the ability to change the value of the _property_; the list remains modifiable (unless you initialize/set the value to an unmodifiable list).&lt;/sup&gt;

&lt;sup&gt;**2.** More specifically, the underlying `ObservableList` value of the `ListProperty` is synchronized with the given `ObservableList`. Though this happens &quot;via the `ListProperty`&quot;.&lt;/sup&gt;


  [1]: https://openjfx.io/javadoc/19/javafx.base/javafx/beans/property/ReadOnlyListProperty.html#bindContent(javafx.collections.ObservableList)
  [2]: https://openjfx.io/javadoc/19/javafx.base/javafx/beans/property/ReadOnlyListProperty.html#bindContentBidirectional(javafx.collections.ObservableList)
  [3]: https://openjfx.io/javadoc/19/javafx.base/javafx/beans/property/ReadOnlyListProperty.html

